PROFESSOR: How do you know where to set it? Well, that's a good question. He's saying, when you're doing a problem like this, how do you know where to pick the reference frame? Well, ask yourself what it is you want to know. And in fact, now that you know that from angular momentum of mechanical things, you can actually get static torques on the system, ask yourself where you want to know those torques.

In this case, if you're designing this, you want to know whether you're going to break this thing off. And it's probably going to break right down at the bottom where the moment arms are the greatest. So that's why you pick that point. It comes a lot with experience will help you choose. But the amazing thing is this information's all stored in the angular momentum if you pick it in the right place. Another hand. OK. Yes, Phillip.

